# Go Project Layout

- `cmd/<service>/main.go` - one deployable binary per directory. Keep `main.go` thin: wire config/dependencies and call into `internal/domain/*`. No business logic in `cmd/` when a domain package exists.
- `internal/platform/*` - thin wrappers around infra: postgres, redis, kafka, clickhouse, inbox, httpx, lifecycle, metrics. No business logic here either - just connection setup and generic helpers (e.g. a generic Inbox-check helper, a generic Kafka consumer-group loop).
- `internal/domain/<billing|messaging|campaigns>/*` - all business logic, organized by bounded context, not by technical layer (no `handlers/`, `services/`, `models/` split across the whole repo). There is no `domain/reporting` package today — reporting HTTP lives in `cmd/reporting-api` on top of sqlc + ClickHouse platform clients; extract a domain package if that surface grows.
- `internal/db/sqlc/*` - generated by `sqlc generate`. Never hand-edit; re-run generation instead (see `.cursor/skills/add-db-query`).
- `db/migrations/*` - `golang-migrate` SQL files, source of truth for the Postgres schema.
- `db/queries/*.sql` - hand-written SQL that `sqlc` compiles.

Rules:
- Dependencies point inward: `cmd` -> `domain` -> `platform`. Never the reverse.
- `domain` packages do not import each other's internals across bounded contexts (e.g. `messaging` must not reach into `billing`). Cross-domain communication happens via Kafka events or explicit, small interfaces passed in at construction time.
- No import cycles - if you need one, you're missing an interface boundary.
- `pkg/` is reserved for code that would make sense as a separate module published outside this repo. Default to `internal/`.
